<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>22</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always"><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Inventory turns</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">: are</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> calculated as the ratio of cost of material compared to the average inventory for the December 3</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">1, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">. For the year ended December 3</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">1, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">, our inventory turns were </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">1.9</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">1compared to </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">4.65</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> for the same period in 2014.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Days Sales in Backlog is calculated based on our back log divided by average daily sales during that period. &#160;For the year ended December 3</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">1, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">, days sales in backlog was </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">349</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> days compared to </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">266 </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">days for the same period in 2014. &#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Days receivables outstanding is calculated as the ratio of average accounts receivable during that period compared to average daily sales for the same period. &#160;For the year ended December 3</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">1, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">, days receivables outstanding was </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">61</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> days compared to </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">39</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> days for the same period in 2014. &#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Days Payable outstanding is calculated as the ratio of average accounts payable during that period compared to average daily sales for the same period. For the year ended December 3</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">1, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">, days payable outstanding was </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">127</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> days compared to </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">68 </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">days for the same period in 2014. &#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">&#160;</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>Cash and Cash Equivalents</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We maintain the majority of its cash accounts at a commercial bank. The total cash balance is insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>FDIC<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) up to $250,000 per commercial bank. For purposes of the statement of cash flows we consider all cash and highly liquid investments with initial maturities of one year or less to be cash equivalents.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Estimates</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities, and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Such estimates may be materially different from actual financial results. Significant estimates include the recoverability of long-lived assets, the collection of accounts receivable and valuation of inventory and reserves.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Accounts Receivable</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We grant credit to our customers located within the United States of America; and do not require collateral. Our ability to collect receivables is affected by economic fluctuations in the geographic areas and industries served by us. &#160;Reserves for un-collectable amounts are provided, based on past experience and a specific analysis of the accounts.&#160; Although we expect to collect amounts due, actual collections may differ from the estimated amounts. As of December 31, 2015, we had a reserve for potentially un-collectable accounts of $7,000.&#160; Five (5) customers accounted for approximately 94% of accounts receivable at December 31, 2015 and one customer accounted for 55% and no other customer accounted for more than 14% of the accounts receivable balance. Our trade accounts primarily represent unsecured receivables.&#160; Historically, our bad debt write-offs related to these trade accounts have been insignificant.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Inventory</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Inventories are valued at the lower of weighted average cost or market value. Our industry experiences changes in technology, changes in market value and availability of raw materials, as well as changing customer demand. We make provisions for estimated excess and obsolete inventories based on regular audits and cycle counts of our on-hand inventory levels and forecasted customer demands and at times additional provisions are made. Any inventory write offs are charged to the reserve account. As of December 31, 2015, we had a reserve for potentially obsolete inventory of $250,000.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>23</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>Property and Equipment </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Property and equipment are stated at cost. Assets held under capital leases are recorded at lease inception at the lower of the present value of the minimum lease payments or the fair market value of the related assets.&#160; We follow the practice of capitalizing property and equipment purchased over $5,000.&#160; The cost of ordinary maintenance and repairs is charged to operations. Depreciation and amortization are computed on the straight-line method over the following estimated useful lives of the related assets:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Furniture and fixtures&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;3 to 7 years</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Equipment&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 7 to 10 years</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Leasehold improvements&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 2 years (life of the lease)</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Long <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8211;</font>Lived Assets</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our management assesses the recoverability of its long-lived assets by determining whether the depreciation and amortization of long lived assets over their remaining lives can be recovered through projected undiscounted future cash flows. The amount of long-lived asset impairment if any, is measured based on fair value and is charged to operations in the period in which long-lived assets impairment is determined by management. There can be no assurance however, that market conditions will not change or demand for our services will continue, which could result in impairment of long-lived assets in the future.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Revenue Recognition</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Revenue from product and services are recognized at the time goods are shipped or services are provided to the customer, with an appropriate provision for returns and allowances. Terms are generally FOB origination with the right of inspection and acceptance. We have not experienced a material amount of rejected or damaged product.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Fair Value of Financial Instruments</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The carrying amount of accounts payable and accrued expenses are considered to be representative of their respective fair values because of the short-term nature of these financial instruments. </P>
<P style="margin:0px">&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Other Comprehensive Income</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px">&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px">We have no material components of other comprehensive income (loss) and accordingly, net loss is equal to comprehensive loss in all periods.</P>
<P style="margin:0px">&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Net Profit/(Loss) per Common Share&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Basic profit / (loss) per share is computed on the basis of the weighted average number of common shares outstanding.&#160; At December 31, 2015, we had outstanding common shares of 139,446,765 used in the calculation of basic earnings per share.&#160; Basic Weighted average common shares and equivalents at December 31, 2015 and 2014 were 59,583,060 and 25,980,566, respectively.&#160; As of December 31, 2015, we had outstanding warrants to purchase 1,050,000 additional common shares and options to purchase 75,122 additional common shares. Fully diluted weighted average common shares and equivalents were withheld from the calculation as they were considered anti-dilutive.&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </B><FONT style="font-size:7pt">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;Research and Development</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We had curtailed all research and development and were focusing our business on its core business of electronics contract manufacturing.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin:0px; color:#000080" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>However, on September 11, 2015 (the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Effective Date<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), Clean Energy HRS LLC (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>CE HRS<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), a wholly owned subsidiary of Probe Manufacturing, Inc. (together with its consolidated subsidiaries, the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), entered into an Asset Purchase Agreement (the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Asset Purchase Agreement<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) with General Electric International, Inc., a Delaware corporation (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), pursuant to which the Company acquired GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s Heat Recovery Solutions (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>HRS<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) assets, including intellectual property, patents, trademarks, machinery, equipment, tooling and fixtures. &#160;The HRS assets will be used by the Company to manufacture and commercialize Organic Rankine Cycle (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>ORC<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>)-based heat recovery power systems. &#160;The ORC system comprises GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>24</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify>proprietary Clean Cycle turbine generator system and integrated power module, together with related components, controls, power electronics, software and equipment. The Company co-locate and integrated the HRS assets with the Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s existing business at the current HRS facility in Costa Mesa, California. We are in the process of analyzing this segment and research and development requirements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Research and Development Costs incurred in association with the alternative fuels technology development (which include salaries and equipment) were expensed as incurred. We had no expenses in Research and Development Costs during the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Segment Information&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>FASB Codification Topic 280, <I>Segment Reporting</I>, establishes standards for reporting financial and descriptive information about an enterprise<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s reportable segments. As identified above in the research and development section, this is a new segment and we are in the process analyzing the appropriate segment information moving forward.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Share Based Compensation&#160;&#160; </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>For a discussion on share based compensation and recently issued accounting pronouncements relating to share based compensation, see Note 2, Basis of Presentation and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies, to our accompanying audited financial statements.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Income Taxes</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>Net Sales&#160; </B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>&#160;</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>For the year ended December 31, 2015, our revenue was $2,355,012 compared to $3,533,502 for the same period in 2014.&#160; Our revenue decreased by $1,178,491 for the year ended December 31, 2015, compared to the same period in 2014. Our revenue decreased because, we made an adjustment to our account base to focus on higher gross profit margin, in addition we experienced down time due to the move to the new facility and the shift of business focus. resulting in departing and making correction to the account base, the move into a new building and nonoperational for several months, and establishing a new sales strategy for newly acquired HRS assets.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>M<B>ajor Customers</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our top 5 customers accounted for approximately 71% of our net sales for the year ended December 31, 2015, compared to 80%, for the same period in 2014. We believe that our ability to grow our core business depends on increasing sales to existing customers, and on successfully attracting new customers. Customer contracts can be canceled and volume levels can be changed or delayed based on our customer<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s performance and the end users<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font> markets they serve which we have no control over. The timely replacement of delayed, canceled or reduced orders with new business cannot be ensured. In addition, we cannot assume that any of our current customers will continue to utilize our services. Consequently, our results of operations may be materially adversely affected.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">&#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>Gross Profit&#160;</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">&#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">For the year </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">ended </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">December 31, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">,</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> our gross profits </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">in</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">creased </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">to </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">27</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">% from </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">21</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">% for the same period in </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">2014</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">. </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Our gross profits could vary from period to period and is affected by a number of factors, including product mix, production efficiencies, component availability and costs, pricing, competition, customer requirements and unanticipated restructuring or inventory charges and potential scrap</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> of materials</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">.&#160; </FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>Selling, General and Administrative (SG&amp;A) Expenses&#160; </B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">&#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">For the year </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">ended </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">December 31, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">,</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> our </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">SG&amp;A expense was </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">28</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">% compared to </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">18</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">% for the same period in </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">2014</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">.&#160;</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">The increase was mainly due to asset acquisition from General Electric.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>Net </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">(Loss)</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> from operations</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">&#160;</FONT></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify>For the year ended December 31, 2015, our net loss from operations was (76%) compared to net loss from operations of (27%) for the same period in 2014. This increase, was primarily due to the acquisition of the Clean Cycle heat recovery system during the year ended 2015.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Loss on impairment of Goodwill</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">On January 2. 2016 we closed the Trident facility in Utah and as for the year ended December 31, 2015 we booked an impairment of the Goodwill in the amount of $420,673.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:8px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Loss on impairment of Inventory</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify>On January 2. 2016 we closed the Trident facility in Utah and as for the year ended December 31, 2015 we booked an impairment of the Inventory of $11,508.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:8px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify><B>Interest Expense</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">For the year ended </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">December 31, 2015</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> interest expense was </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">$</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">3</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">53,476</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> compared to </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">$</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">313,254</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"> for the same period in </FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">2014</FONT><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify><B>Net Income / Loss</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:6.667px" align=justify>For the year ended December 31, 2015, our net loss was (109%) compared to net loss of (35)% for the same period in 2014. This increase was primarily due to acquisition of the Clean Cycle heat recovery system assets during the year ended 2015. In addition, we recognized $420, 673 in goodwill impairment, as a result of the closure of the Trident facility.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B><I>Critical Accounting Policies</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">Our financial statements and accompanying notes have been prepared in accordance with United States generally accepted accounting principles applied on a consistent basis. The preparation of financial statements in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities, the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting periods.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">We regularly evaluate the accounting policies and estimates that we use to prepare our financial statements. A complete summary of these policies is included in the notes to our financial statements. In general, management's estimates are based on historical experience, on information from third party professionals, and on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the facts and circumstances. Actual results could differ from those estimates made by management.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF"><B>Future Financing</B></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><FONT style="background-color:#FFFFFF">We will continue to rely on equity sales of our common shares in order to continue to fund our business operations. Issuances of additional shares will result in dilution to existing stockholders. There is no assurance that we will achieve any additional sales of the equity securities or arrange for debt or other financing to fund planned acquisitions and exploration activities.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Off-balance Sheet Arrangement</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We have no significant off-balance sheet arrangements that have or are reasonably likely to have a current or future effect on our financial condition, changes in financial condition, revenues or expenses, results of operations, liquidity, capital expenditures or capital resources that are material to stockholders.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Contractual Obligations</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We are a smaller reporting company as defined by Rule 12b-2 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 and are not required to provide the information under this item.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company has implemented all new accounting pronouncements that are in effect. These pronouncements did not have any material impact on the financial statements unless otherwise disclosed, and the Company does not believe that there are any other new accounting pronouncements that have been issued that might have a material impact on its financial position or results of operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Item 7a.</B> <B>Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures about Market Risk.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We are a smaller reporting company as defined by Rule 12b-2 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 and are not required to provide the information under this item.</P>

<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:6.667px; font-family:'Arial'" align=center>REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM</P>
<P style="margin:8px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:6.667px; font-family:'Arial'">To the Board of Directors andStockholders of Clean Energy Technologies, Inc.</P>
<P style="margin:8px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:6.667px; font-family:'Arial'" align=justify>We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of Clean Energy Technologies, Inc. as of December 31, 2015 and 2014, and the related consolidated statements of income, stockholders<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Arial'">&#8217;</font> equity, and cash flows for the two years ended December 31, 2015. Clean Energy Technologies, Inc.<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Arial'">&#8217;</font>s management is responsible for these financial statements. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits.</P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:6.667px; font-family:'Arial'" align=justify>We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement. The company is not required to have, nor were we engaged to perform, an audit of its internal control over financial reporting. Our audit included consideration of internal control over financial reporting as a basis for designing audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Arial'">&#8217;</font>s internal control over financial reporting. Accordingly, we express no such opinion. An audit also includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements, assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.</P>
<P style="margin-top:6.667px; margin-bottom:6.667px; font-family:'Arial'" align=justify>In our opinion, the financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of Clean Energy Technologies, Inc. as of December 31, 2015 and 2014, and the results of its operations and its cash flows for the two years ended December 31, 2015, in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:8.867px; font-family:'Arial'" align=justify>The accompanying consolidated financial statements have been prepared assuming the Company will continue as a going concern.&#160; As discussed in Note 1 to the financial statements, the Company has a history of operating losses, has limited cash resources, and its viability is dependent upon its ability to meet future financing requirements. These factors raise substantial doubt about the Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Arial'">&#8217;</font>s ability to continue as a going concern.&#160;Management<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Arial'">&#8217;</font>s plans in regard to these matters are also described in Note 1.&#160;The financial statements do not include any adjustments that might result from the outcome of this uncertainty.</P>

<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=center><B>Clean Energy Technologies, Inc.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>(f/k/a Probe Manufacturing, Inc.)</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>&#160;Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Notes 1- GENERAL</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>The Company</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>Clean Energy Technologies, Inc. (f/k/a Probe Manufacturing, Inc.) (the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Company,<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Clean Energy,<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> or <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>CETY<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) headquartered in Costa Mesa, California<FONT style="font-size:11.5pt">, </FONT>designs, builds and markets clean energy products focused on energy efficiency and environmentally sustainable technologies. The Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s principal product is the Clean Cycle<SUP>TM</SUP> generator, offered by its wholly owned subsidiary Heat Recovery Solutions. The Heat Recovery Solutions system captures waste heat from a variety of sources and turns it into electricity that users can use or sell back to the grid. CETY<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s proven cutting-edge technology allows any commercial or industrial heat generators to boost their overall energy efficiency with no fuel, no pollutants and virtually no maintenance.&#160;Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s engineering and manufacturing resources support its heat recovery solutions business, as well as continuing to support other Clean Energy emerging growth companies with their technologies. CETY is positioned to become a worldwide leader in an ever expanding energy efficiency market.<FONT style="background-color:#FFFF00"> </FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our growth strategy is to scale our business by focusing on new market segments &amp; regions in the fuel, incentive and process markets, sell equipment direct and through the global distribution channels, build and lease systems sites in island nations to offset the cost of their diesel fuel &amp; emissions, license patented technology and proprietary process, develop cogeneration and OEM opportunities and develop higher output generators while lowering cost. &nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our initial acquisition in clean energy is the proprietary turbine technology for Organic Rankine Cycle (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>ORC<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>)-based heat recovery power systems, which matches our manufacturing and engineering strengths. Our engineering and manufacturing services also provide a source of revenue and assist in providing opportunities for potential business and intellectual property acquisitions.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On September 11, 2015, Clean Energy HRS LLC (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>CE HRS<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), a wholly owned subsidiary of the Company, entered into an Asset Purchase Agreement with General Electric International, Inc., a Delaware corporation (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), pursuant to which CE HRS acquired GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s Heat Recovery Solutions, or HRS, assets, including intellectual property, patents, trademarks, machinery, equipment, tooling and fixtures. The HRS assets will be used by the Company to manufacture and commercialize Organic Rankine Cycle (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>ORC<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>)-based heat recovery power systems. The ORC system comprised GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s proprietary Clean Cycle<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8482;</font> turbine generator system and integrated power module, together with related components, controls, power electronics, software and equipment. The Company co-located and integrate the HRS assets with the Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s existing engineering and manufacturing business at the former GEII facility in Costa Mesa, California. &nbsp;The consideration for the purchase of the HRS assets was set forth in the Asset Purchase Agreement, which was filed as Exhibit 10.1 to the Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s Current Report on Form 8K dated September 11, 2015. &nbsp;CE HRS issued a three-year promissory note to GEII with respect to payment of the cash portion of the purchase price and CE HRS assumed certain liabilities of GEII related to the acquired assets. In connection with the Asset Purchase Agreement, the Company also entered into various ancillary agreements customary for asset acquisition transactions of this type.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:11.133px">In connection with the HRS asset transaction, on September 15, 2015, the Company entered into a Transaction Completion and Financing Agreement (the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>TCF Agreement<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) with ETI Partners IV LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>ETI<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), pursuant to which the Company and ETI implemented a structure to provide for the Company to raise up to $5,000,000 in financing. In connection with the TCF Agreement, the Company agreed to issue to ETI 104,910,321 shares of restricted common stock, representing 70% of the fully diluted common stock of the Company upon receipt of an initial $500,000 in financing, which occurred during the quarter ending December 31, 2015. In conjunction with the TCF Agreement, the Company and ETI also entered into a Loan, Guarantee, and Collateral Agreement (the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Loan Agreement<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) and a Registration Rights Agreement. Financing to the Company is intended to be provided pursuant to the Loan Agreement and any shares issued or issuable in connection with the financing are granted certain demand registration rights pursuant to the Registration Rights Agreement. Pursuant to the TCF Agreement, the Company expanded its Board of Directors to 11 directors, and ETI nominated and elected five persons to the Board of Directors. In connection with the TCF Agreement, the Company also entered into various ancillary agreements customary for investment loan transactions of this type. On October 2, 2015, the Company issued an aggregate of 100,910,321 shares of common stock to one investor pursuant to the Transaction Completion and Financing Agreement and 4,000,000 to one investor. &nbsp;All such shares were issued to the accredited investors for cash of $500,000.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>36</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; page-break-before:always" align=justify>ETI Capital Partners IV (ETI) acquired a 70 % interest in Clean Energy Technologies, Inc. (CETI) formerly Probe Manufacturing, Inc. for $300,000 in cash. on October 1,<SUP> </SUP>2015. This transaction resulted in a change of control. According to FASB No. 2014-17 Business Combinations (Topic 805) and as a result, this transaction does qualify as a business combination, ETI is not an investment company. &nbsp;CETI elected to apply pushdown accounting, using the valuation date of September 30, 2015. &nbsp;As a result, we recognized $747,976 in goodwill</P>

</TD></TR>

</TD><TD style="margin-top:0px; padding-left:6px; padding-top:0px; padding-right:6px; padding-bottom:0px" valign=bottom width=179.2 height=20><P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>

</TD><TD style="margin-top:0px; padding-left:6px; padding-top:0px; padding-right:6px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color:#D7FFD7" valign=bottom width=179.2 height=20><P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD style="margin-top:0px; padding-left:6px; padding-top:0px; padding-right:6px; padding-bottom:0px" valign=bottom height=20><P style="margin:0px; font-size:11pt">Cash Received</P>
</TD><TD style="margin-top:0px; padding-left:6px; padding-top:0px; padding-right:6px; padding-bottom:0px" valign=bottom width=179.2 height=20><P style="margin:0px; font-size:11pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;300,000 </P>

</TD></TR>
<TR><TD style="margin-top:0px; padding-left:6px; padding-top:0px; padding-right:6px; padding-bottom:0px" valign=bottom height=20><P style="margin:0px; font-size:11pt">Equity</P>
</TD><TD style="margin-top:0px; padding-left:6px; padding-top:0px; padding-right:6px; padding-bottom:0px" valign=bottom width=179.2 height=20><P style="margin:0px; font-size:11pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;1,047,976 </P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>As part of completing the acquisition of the HRS assets pursuant to the Asset Purchase Agreement and the TCF Agreement and integration thereof into our business, we changed our name to <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Clean Energy Technologies, Inc.<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> on November 13, 2015to better reflect the focus of our new business and business strategies. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Previously, in March 2013, pursuant to an Agreement and Plan of Acquisition with Trident Manufacturing, Inc., a Utah corporation (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Trident<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) and the shareholders of Trident, we acquired 100% of the issued and outstanding common stock shares of Trident in exchange for 1,600,000 shares of our restricted shares of common stock. As a result of the acquisition, Trident became a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Company. &nbsp;Trident is a full-service electronics manufacturing services company with a 16,000 sq. ft. manufacturing facility in Salt Lake City, Utah, servicing the industrial, aerospace, military, instrumentation, and medical markets since 2005.As of the Trident acquisition, we recognized $420,673 in goodwill. &nbsp;For the year ended December 31, 2015, we impaired the goodwill in the amount of $420,673.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Going Concern</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">The financial statements have been prepared on a going concern basis, which contemplates continuity of operations, realization of assets and liquidation of liabilities in the normal course of business. The Company had a total stockholder<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s deficit of $1,249,843 and a working capital deficit of $2,012,417 and a net loss of $2,569,936 for the year ended December 31, 2015. The company also had an accumulated deficit of $4,875,138 as of December 31, 2015 and used $617,553 in net cash from operating activities for the year ended December 31, 2015. Therefore, there is substantial doubt about the ability of the Company to continue as a going concern. There can be no assurance that the Company will achieve its goals and reach a profitable operating stand and is still dependent upon its ability (1) to obtain sufficient debt and/or equity capital and/or (2) to generate positive cash flow from operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Plan of Operation</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px">Management is taking the following steps to sustain profitability and growth: (i) increase sales through existing global distribution channels and utilization of direct sales (ii) sell electricity by kWH to Island nations where the cost of energy is higher and it can offset the cost of their fuel and reduce emissions.(iii) leveraging core competencies to acquire technologies and entertain equity opportunities and (iv) license patented technology and proprietary process and develop cogeneration and OEM opportunities.</P>
<P style="line-height:12pt; margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="line-height:12pt; margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>37</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="line-height:12pt; margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Our future success is likely dependent on our ability to sustain profitable growth and attain additional capital to support growth. There can be no assurance that we will be successful in obtaining any such financing, or that it will be able to generate sufficient positive cash flow from operations. &#160;The successful outcome of these or any future activities cannot be determined at this time and there is no assurance that if achieved, we will have sufficient funds to execute its business plans. The financial statements do not include any adjustments relating to the recoverability and classification of asset carrying amounts or the amount and classification of liabilities that might result should we be unable to continue as a going concern. &#160;</P>
<P style="line-height:12pt; margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Our Products and Services </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our main product, the Clean Cycle<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8482;</font> HRS system, converts heat from variety of heat sources into clean, affordable electricity. Our heat recovery solution system generates electricity from heat with zero fuel required, zero emissions produced, and low maintenance. &nbsp;The Clean Cycle<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8482;</font> HRS system is also re-deployable with continuous 24x7 operation.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Sales and Marketing </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our marketing approach is to position the Company, our products and our services under our new <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Clean Energy Technologies, Inc.<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> and <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>CETY<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> identity and brand. &nbsp;We intend to market our Heat Recovery Solutions products specifically using the market-recognized Clean Cycle<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8482;</font> brand name. &nbsp;We also intend to utilize our relationships to identify new market segments and regions in which we can expand the commercialization of our products. &nbsp;We intend to offer our products for sale and also to commercialize them under leases, energy-based contracts and other financing structures to accelerate customer adoption and increase market penetration. &nbsp;We also intend to explore licensing opportunities for our patented and other proprietary technologies. We utilize both direct sales force and global distributors with expertise in clean energy. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>NOTE 2 <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8211;</font> BASIS OF PRESENTATION AND SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES:</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The summary of significant accounting policies of Clean Energy Technologies, Inc. (formerly Probe Manufacturing, Inc.) is presented to assist in the understanding of the Company's financial statements. The financial statements and notes are representations of the Company's management, who is responsible for their integrity and objectivity.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Estimates</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities, and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Such estimates may be materially different from actual financial results. Significant estimates include the recoverability of long-lived assets, the collection of accounts receivable and valuation of inventory and reserves.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Cash and Cash Equivalents</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We maintain the majority of our cash accounts at a commercial bank. The total cash balance is insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>FDIC<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) up to $250,000 per commercial bank. For purposes of the statement of cash flows we consider all cash and highly liquid investments with initial maturities of one year or less to be cash equivalents.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Accounts Receivable</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We grant credit to our customers located within the United States of America; and do not require collateral. Our ability to collect receivables is affected by economic fluctuations in the geographic areas and industries served by us. &#160;Reserves for un-collectable amounts are provided, based on past experience and a specific analysis of the accounts.&#160; Although we expect to collect amounts due, actual collections may differ from the estimated amounts. As of December 31, 2015, we had a reserve for potentially un-collectable accounts of $7,000.&#160; Five (5) customers accounted for approximately 94% of accounts receivable at December 31, 2015 and one customer accounted for 55% and no other customer accounted for more than 14% of the accounts receivable balance. Our trade accounts primarily represent unsecured receivables.&#160; Historically, our bad debt write-offs related to these trade accounts have been insignificant.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Inventory</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>38</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify>Inventories are valued at the lower of weighted average cost or market value. Our industry experiences changes in technology, changes in market value and availability of raw materials, as well as changing customer demand. We make provisions for estimated excess and obsolete inventories based on regular audits and cycle counts of our on-hand inventory levels and forecasted customer demands and at times additional provisions are made. Any inventory write offs are charged to the reserve account. As of December 31, 2015, we had a reserve for potentially obsolete inventory of $250,000.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Property and Equipment </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Property and equipment are recorded at cost. Assets held under capital leases are recorded at lease inception at the lower of the present value of the minimum lease payments or the fair market value of the related assets.&#160; The cost of ordinary maintenance and repairs is charged to operations. Depreciation and amortization are computed on the straight-line method over the following estimated useful lives of the related assets:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Furniture and fixtures&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 3 to 7 years</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Equipment&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 7 to 10 years</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Depreciation expense totaled $38, 145 and $42,108 for the year ended December 31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Long <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8211;</font>Lived Assets</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Our management assesses the recoverability of its long-lived assets by determining whether the depreciation and amortization of long lived assets over their remaining lives can be recovered through projected undiscounted future cash flows. The amount of long-lived asset impairment if any, is measured based on fair value and is charged to operations in the period in which long-lived assets impairment is determined by management. There can be no assurance however, that market conditions will not change or demand for our services will continue, which could result in impairment of long-lived assets in the future.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Revenue Recognition</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Revenue from product and services are recognized at the time goods are shipped or services are provided to the customer, with an appropriate provision for returns and allowances. Terms are generally FOB origination with the right of inspection and acceptance. We have not experienced a material amount of rejected or damaged product.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The Company provides services for its customers that range from contract design to original product design to repair services. The Company recognizes service revenue when the services have been performed, and the related costs are expensed as incurred.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Fair Value of Financial Instruments</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>The carrying amount of accounts payable and accrued expenses are considered to be representative of their respective fair values because of the short-term nature of these financial instruments. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Other Comprehensive Income</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We have no material components of other comprehensive income (loss) and accordingly, net loss is equal to comprehensive loss in all periods.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Net Profit (Loss) per Common Share&#160;&#160;&#160; </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Basic profit / (loss) per share is computed on the basis of the weighted average number of common shares outstanding.&#160; At December 31, 2015, we had outstanding common shares of 139,446,765 used in the calculation of basic earnings per share.&#160; Basic Weighted average common shares and equivalents at December 31, 2015 and 2014 were 59,583,060 and 25,980,566, respectively.&#160; As of December 31, 2015, we had outstanding warrants to purchase 1,050,000 additional common shares and options to purchase 75,122 additional common shares. Fully diluted weighted average common shares and equivalents were withheld from the calculation as they were considered anti-dilutive.&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Research and Development</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>39</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify>We had curtailed all research and development and were focusing our business on its core business of electronics contract manufacturing.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin:0px; color:#000080" align=justify><B>&#160;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>However, on September 11, 2015 (the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Effective Date<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), Clean Energy HRS LLC (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>CE HRS<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), a wholly owned subsidiary of Probe Manufacturing, Inc. (together with its consolidated subsidiaries, the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), entered into an Asset Purchase Agreement (the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Asset Purchase Agreement<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) with General Electric International, Inc., a Delaware corporation (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), pursuant to which the Company acquired GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s Heat Recovery Solutions (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>HRS<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>) assets, including intellectual property, patents, trademarks, machinery, equipment, tooling and fixtures. &#160;The HRS assets will be used by the Company to manufacture and commercialize Organic Rankine Cycle (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>ORC<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>)-based heat recovery power systems. &#160;The ORC system comprises GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s proprietary Clean Cycle turbine generator system and integrated power module, together with related components, controls, power electronics, software and equipment. The Company co-locate and integrated the HRS assets with the Company<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s existing business at the current HRS facility in Costa Mesa, California. We are in the process of analyzing this segment and research and development requirements.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>Research and Development Costs incurred in association with the alternative fuels technology development (which include salaries and equipment) were expensed as incurred. We had no expenses in Research and Development Costs during the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B>Segment Information&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>FASB Codification Topic 280, <I>Segment Reporting</I>, establishes standards for reporting financial and descriptive information about an enterprise<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s reportable segments. As identified above in the research and development section, this is a new segment and we are in the process analyzing the appropriate segment information moving forward.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify><B>Share-Based Compensation&#160;&#160; </B></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>The Company has adopted the use of Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 123R, <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Share-Based Payment<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> (SFAS No.&#160;123R) (now contained in FASB Codification Topic 718, <I>Compensation-Stock Compensation</I>), which supersedes APB Opinion No. 25, <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>Accounting for Stock Issued to Employees,<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> and its related implementation guidance and eliminates the alternative to use Opinion 25<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font>s intrinsic value method of accounting that was provided in Statement 123 as originally issued. This Statement requires an entity to measure the cost of employee services received in exchange for an award of an equity instruments, which includes grants of stock options and stock warrants, based on the fair value of the award, measured at the grant date (with limited exceptions). Under this standard, the fair value of each award is estimated on the grant date, using an option-pricing model that meets certain requirements. We use the Black-Scholes option-pricing model to estimate the fair value of our equity awards, including stock options and warrants. The Black-Scholes model meets the requirements of SFAS No.&#160;123R; however, the fair values generated may not reflect their actual fair values, as it does not consider certain factors, such as vesting requirements, employee attrition and transferability limitations. The Black-Scholes model valuation is affected by our stock price and a number of assumptions, including expected volatility, expected life, risk-free interest rate and expected dividends. We estimate the expected volatility and estimated life of our stock options at grant date based on historical volatility; however, due to the thinly traded nature of our stock, we have chosen to use an average of the annual volatility of like companies in our industry. For the <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>risk-free interest rate,<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font> we use the Constant Maturity Treasury rate on 90-day government securities. The term is equal to the time until the option expires. The dividend yield is not applicable, as the Company has not paid any dividends, nor do we anticipate paying them in the foreseeable future. The fair value of our restricted stock is based on the market value of our free trading common stock, on the grant date calculated using a 20-trading-day average. At the time of grant, the share-based compensation expense is recognized in our financial statements based on awards that are ultimately expected to vest using historical employee attrition rates and the expense is reduced accordingly.&#160; It is also adjusted to account for the restricted and thinly traded nature of the shares.&#160; The expense is reviewed and adjusted in subsequent periods if actual attrition differs from those estimates. </P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>We re-evaluate the assumptions used to value our share-based awards on a quarterly basis and, if changes warrant different assumptions, the share-based compensation expense could vary significantly from the amount expensed in the past. We may be required to adjust any remaining share-based compensation expense, based on any additions, cancellations or adjustments to the share-based awards. The expense is recognized over the period during which an employee is required to provide service in exchange for the award<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8212;</font>the requisite service period (usually the vesting period). No compensation cost is recognized for equity instruments for which employees do not render the requisite service.&#160;&#160;For the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014 we had $85,450 and $160,000 respectively, in share based expense, due to the issuance of common stock.&#160; As of December 31, 2015 we had no further non-vested expense to be recognized.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; font-size:12pt" align=center>40</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><B>Income Taxes</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>The Company accounts for income taxes under SFAS No. 109 (now contained in FASB Codification Topic 740-10-25, Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes), which requires the asset and liability approach to accounting for income taxes.&#160; Under this method, deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured based on differences between financial reporting and tax bases of assets and liabilities measured using enacted tax rates and laws that are expected to be in effect when differences are expected to reverse. As of December 31, 2015, we had a net operating loss carry-forward of approximately $5,000,000 and a deferred tax asset of approximately $1,731,293&#160;using the statutory rate of 34%. The deferred tax asset may be recognized in future periods, not to exceed 20 years.&#160; However, due to the uncertainty of future events we have booked valuation allowance of $(1,731,293). &nbsp;FASB ASC 740 prescribes recognition threshold and measurement attributes for the financial statement recognition and measurement of a tax position taken or expected to be taken in a tax return. FASB ASC 740 also provides guidance on de-recognition, classification, interest and penalties, accounting in interim periods, disclosure and transition. &nbsp;At December 31, 2015, the Company had not taken any tax positions that would require disclosure under FASB ASC 740.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We are subject to taxation in the U.S. and the states of California and Utah. &nbsp;Further, the Company currently has no open tax years<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font> subject to audit prior to December 31, 2012. &nbsp;The Company is current on its federal and state tax returns.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Reclassification</B></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px" align=justify>Certain amounts in the prior period financial statements have been reclassified to conform to the current period presentation. These reclassifications had no effect on reported income, total assets, or stockholders<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8217;</font> equity as previously reported.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Business Combination and Goodwill</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>On March 20, 2013, we completed the acquisition of Trident whereby we acquired 100% of the issued and outstanding common stock shares of Trident in exchange for 1,600,000 shares of our restricted shares of common stock. As a result of the acquisition, Trident has become a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Company. As a result, we recognized $420,673 in goodwill. &nbsp;On January 2. 2016 we closed the Trident facility in Utah and as for the year ended December 31, 2015 we booked an impairment of the Goodwill in the amount of $420,673.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>NOTE 8 <font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8211;</font> NOTES PAYABLE</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#160;</P>
<P style="line-height:12pt; margin:0px" align=justify><B>Notes payable</B></P>
<P style="line-height:12pt; margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>The Company issued a short-term note payable to an individual, secured by the assets of the Company, dated September 6, 2013 in the amount of $50,000 and fixed fee amount of $3,500. As of December 31, 2015 the outstanding balance was $38,500<FONT style="color:#FF0000">.</FONT></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>On November 11, 2013, we entered in to an accounts receivable financing agreement with American Interbanc (now Nations Interbanc). &nbsp;Amounts outstanding under the agreement bear interest at the rate of 2.5% per month. &nbsp;It is secured by the assets of the Company. &nbsp;In addition, it is personally guaranteed by Kambiz Mahdi, our Chief Executive Officer. As of December 31, 2015, the outstanding balance was $786,227, compared to $393,399 at December 31, 2014.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>On November 3, 2009, the Company issued an unsecured note payable to Linwood Goddard at a 12.00% interest rate, with a 36-month amortization and monthly payments of $334.14.&#160; At December 31, 2015, the outstanding balance was $4,332.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>On December 24, 2009, the Company issued an unsecured note payable to Linwood Goddard at a 12.00% interest rate, with a 36-month amortization and monthly payments of $334.14.&#160; At December 31, 2015, the outstanding balance was $4,332.&#160; </P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>On August 28, 2014, we issued an unsecured note for $100,000 with a fixed fee of $20,000, amortized over 7 months. &nbsp;On December 22, 2014, the outstanding balance of this note including remaining fees was $58,441, when the outstanding balance was rolled into a new note in the initial principal amount of $150,000, with fees in the amount of $28,500. &nbsp;The new note amortizes over 18 months. &nbsp;The outstanding balance at December 31, 2015 was $59,331.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>On September 11, 2015, our CE HRS subsidiary issued a promissory note in the initial principal amount $1,400,000 and assumed a pension liability of $100,000, for a total liability of $1,500,000, in connection with our acquisition of the heat recovery solutions, or HRS, assets of General Electric International, Inc., a Delaware corporation (<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8220;</font>GEII<font style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS,Times New Roman'">&#8221;</font>), including intellectual property, patents, trademarks, machinery, equipment, tooling and fixtures. &nbsp;The note bears interest at the rate of 2.66% per annum. &nbsp;The note is payable on the following schedule: (a) $200,000 in principal on December 31, 2015 and (b) thereafter, the remaining principal amount of $1,200,000, together with interest thereon, payable in equal quarterly installments of principal and interest of $157,609.02, commencing on December 31, 2016 and continuing until June 30, 2018, at which time the remaining unpaid principal amount of this note and all accrued and unpaid interest thereon shall be due and payable in full. </P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Operating Rental Leases</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>

The facility is approximately 15,040 square feet and located at 440 West Lawndale Drive, Salt Lake City UT 84115.</P>

<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Severance Benefits </I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>Effective at December 31, 2015, Mr. Mahdi was entitled to receive in the event of his termination without cause a severance benefit consisting of a single lump sum cash payment equal the salary that Mr. Mahdi would have been entitled to receive period of (1) year, at an annual salary of $275,000.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:11.133px" align=justify>Effective at December 31, 2015, Mr. Bennett was entitled to receive in the event of his termination without cause a severance benefit consisting of a single lump sum cash payment equal the salary that Mr. Bennett would have been entitled to receive through the remainder of his employment period or two (2) years, whichever is greater, at an annual salary of $140,000.</P>
